It is sponsored by the Bank for International Settlements (BIS), the European Central Bank (ECB), the Statistical Office of the European Union (Eurostat), the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the Organization for Economic Co-Operation and Development (OECD), the United Nations (UN) and the World Bank.</com:Description>           <str:Contact>             <com:Name xml:lang="en">SDMX Secretariat</com:Name>             <str:Department xml:lang="en">SDMX Secretariat</str:Department>             <str:Role xml:lang="en">Single entry point for external inquiries</str:Role>             <str:Email>secretariat@sdmx.org</str:Email>             <str:URI>http://sdmx.org</str:URI>           </str:Contact>         </str:Agency>         <str:Agency id="IMF" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.base.Agency=IMF">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">International Monetary Fund (IMF)</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">The IMF works to foster global growth and economic stability. It provides policy advice and financing to members in economic difficulties and also works with developing nations to help them achieve macroeconomic stability and reduce poverty.</com:Description>           <str:Contact>             <com:Name xml:lang="en">Single point of contact for external inquiries</com:Name>             <str:Department xml:lang="en">Statistics Department</str:Department>             <str:Role xml:lang="en">Single point of contact for external inquiries</str:Role>             <str:Email>StatisticsQuery@imf.org</str:Email>             <str:URI>http://www.imf.org</str:URI>           </str:Contact>         </str:Agency>         <str:Agency id="ESTAT" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.base.Agency=ESTAT">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Statistical Office of the European Union (Eurostat)</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Eurostat is the statistical office of the European Union situated in Luxembourg. Its task is to provide the European Union with high quality statistics at European level that enable comparisons between countries and regions. Website: http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/.</com:Description>           <str:Contact>             <com:Name xml:lang="en">SDMX Support</com:Name>             <str:Department xml:lang="en">Various units involved in SDMX</str:Department>             <str:Role xml:lang="en">SDMX Support</str:Role>             <str:Email>estat-support-sdmx@ec.europa.eu</str:Email>             <str:URI>http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/</str:URI>           </str:Contact>         </str:Agency>         <str:Agency id="UNESCO" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.base.Agency=UNESCO">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">United Nations Organization for Education, Science and Culture (UNESCO)</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">The United Nations Organization for Education, Science and Culture (UNESCO) was founded on 16 November 1945.  UNESCO has 195 Members and eight Associate Members. It is governed by the General Conference and the Executive Board. The Secretariat, headed by the Director-General, implements the decisions of these two bodies.  The Organization has more than 50 field offices around the world. Its headquarters are located at Place de Fontenoy in Paris, France, in in an outstanding, Modernist building inaugurated in 1958 and recently renovated.</com:Description>         </str:Agency>         <str:Agency id="OECD" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.base.Agency=OECD">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD)</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">The mission of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) is to promote policies that will improve the economic and social well-being of people around the world.  The OECD provides a forum in which governments can work together to share experiences and seek solutions to common problems. We work with governments to understand what drives economic, social and environmental change. We measure productivity and global flows of trade and investment. We analyse and compare data to predict future trends. We set international standards on a wide range of things, from agriculture and tax to the safety of chemicals.  We look, too, at issues that directly affect the lives of ordinary people, like how much they pay in taxes and social security, and how much leisure time they can take. We compare how different countries\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd school systems are readying their young people for modern life, and how different countries\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd pension systems will look after their citizens in old age.  Drawing on facts and real-life experience, we recommend policies designed to make the lives of ordinary people better. We work with business, through the Business and Industry Advisory Committee to the OECD, and with labour, through the Trade Union Advisory Committee. We have active contacts as well with other civil society organisations. The common thread of our work is a shared commitment to market economies backed by democratic institutions and focused on the wellbeing of all citizens. Along the way, we also set out to make life harder for the terrorists, tax dodgers, crooked businessmen and others whose actions undermine a fair and open society.</com:Description>         </str:Agency>       </str:AgencyScheme>     </str:OrganisationSchemes>     <str:Codelists>       <str:Codelist id="CL_ACTIVITY" <str:Codelist id="CL_CONF_STATUS" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Codelist=SDMX:CL_CONF_STATUS(1.0)" agencyID="SDMX" version="1.0" isFinal="true">         <com:Name xml:lang="en">Confidentiality Status</com:Name>         <com:Description xml:lang="en">This code list provides coded information about the sensitivity and confidentiality status of the data.   This code list was first released in 2009.  More information about this code list and SDMX code lists in general (e.g. list of generic codes for expressing general concepts like "Total", "Unknown", etc.; syntaxes for the creation of further codes; general guidelines for the creation of SDMX code lists) can be found at this address: http://sdmx.org/?page_id=1513.</com:Description>         <str:Code id="F" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_CONF_STATUS(1.0).F">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Free</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">It is used for observations for which there are no special sensitivity considerations and which can be freely shared. Please note:   In some institutional environments the term "unclassified" is used in a sense that still denotes implied restrictions in the circulation of information. If this is the case, this organisation may probably consider that "free" (value F) is not the appropriate corresponding tag for this kind of "unclassified" category and it may be that "non-publishable / restricted" (value N) may be more appropriate. The focus of this code is not to describe and anticipate all potential permissible uses (e.g. permission to re-disseminate). Thus, the use of "F" does not allow safe assumptions with respect to the permission to "re-disseminate" (freely or at a price) the received or accessed information (e.g. on web or paper), especially on a massive and regular basis (legal and copyright constraints may apply). Usually, source organisations provide information and guidance on re-dissemination issues, either on their websites or on their paper publications.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="N" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_CONF_STATUS(1.0).N">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Not for publication, restricted for internal use only</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Used to denote observations that are restricted for internal use only within organisations.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="C" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_CONF_STATUS(1.0).C">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Confidential statistical information</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Confidential statistical information (primary confidentiality) due to identifiable respondents.  Measures also should be taken to prevent not only direct access, but also indirect deduction or calculation by other users and parties, probably by considering and treating additional observations as "confidential" (secondary confidentiality management).</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="D" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_CONF_STATUS(1.0).D">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Secondary confidentiality set by the sender, not for publication</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Used by the sender of the data to flag (beyond the confidential statistical information) one or more additional observations of the dataset so that the receiver knows that he/she should suppress these observations in subsequent stages of processing (especially, dissemination) in order to prevent third parties to indirectly deduct (e.g. through accounting identities or other formulas) the observations that are genuinely flagged with "C".</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="S" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_CONF_STATUS(1.0).S">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Secondary confidentiality set and managed by the receiver, not for publication</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">If senders do not manage the secondary confidentiality in their data and/or there are also other countries' data involved (with the intention to eventually compile a regional-wide aggregate that is going to be published), the value "S" is used by the receiver to flag additional suppressed observations (within sender's data and/or within the datasets of other senders) in subsequent stages of processing (especially, dissemination) in order to prevent third parties to indirectly deduct the observations that were genuinely flagged with "C" by the sender</com:Description>         </str:Code>       </str:Codelist>       <str:Codelist id="CL_DECIMALS" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_DECIMALS(1.0).15">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Fifteen</com:Name>         </str:Code>       </str:Codelist>       <str:Codelist id="CL_FREQ" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Codelist=SDMX:CL_FREQ(2.0)" agencyID="SDMX" version="2.0" isFinal="true">         <com:Name xml:lang="en">Frequency</com:Name>         <com:Description xml:lang="en">This code list provides a set of values indicating the "frequency" of the data (e.g. weekly, monthly, quarterly). The concept \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdfrequency\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd may refer to various stages in the production process, e.g. data collection or data dissemination. For example, a time series could be disseminated at annual frequency but the underlying data are compiled monthly. The code list is applicable for all different uses of "frequency". This code list was formally adopted on 4 December 2013. More information about and supporting material for this code list and SDMX code lists in general (e.g. list of generic codes for expressing general concepts like "Total", "Unknown", etc.; syntaxes for the creation of further codes; general guidelines for the creation of SDMX code lists) can be found at this address: http://sdmx.org/?page_id=1513.</com:Description>         <str:Code id="A" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_FREQ(2.0).A">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Annual</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every year.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="S" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_FREQ(2.0).S">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Half-yearly, semester</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every semester.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="Q" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_FREQ(2.0).Q">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Quarterly</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every quarter.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="M" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_FREQ(2.0).M">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Monthly</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every month.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="W" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_FREQ(2.0).W">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Weekly</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every week.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="D" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_FREQ(2.0).D">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Daily</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every day.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="H" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_FREQ(2.0).H">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Hourly</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every hour.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="B" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_FREQ(2.0).B">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Daily \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd businessweek</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Similar to "daily", however there are no observations for Saturdays and Sundays (so, neither "missing values" nor "numeric values" should be provided for Saturday and Sunday). This treatment  ("business") is one way to deal with such cases, but it is not the only option. Such a time series could alternatively be considered daily ("D"), thus, with missing values in the weekend.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="N" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_FREQ(2.0).N">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Minutely</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">While N denotes "minutely", usually, there may be no observations every minute (for several series the frequency is usually "irregular" within a day/days). And though observations may be sparse (not collected or disseminated every minute), missing values do not need to be given for the minutes when no observations exist: in any case the time stamp determines when an observation is observed.</com:Description>         </str:Code>       </str:Codelist>       <str:Codelist id="CL_OBS_STATUS" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Codelist=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1)" agencyID="SDMX" version="1.1" isFinal="true">         <com:Name xml:lang="en">Observation Status</com:Name>         <com:Description xml:lang="en">This code list provides coded information on 1) the quality of a value or 2) unusual or missing values. It was formally adopted on 20 September 2013. More information about this code list and SDMX code lists in general (e.g. list of generic codes for expressing general concepts like "Total", "Unknown", etc.; syntaxes for the creation of further codes; general guidelines for the creation of SDMX code lists) can be found at this address: http://sdmx.org/?page_id=1513.</com:Description>         <str:Code id="A" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).A">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Normal</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">To be used as default value if no value is provided or when no special coded qualification is assumed. Usually, it can be assumed that the source agency assigns sufficient confidence to the provided observation and/or the value is not expected to be dramatically revised.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="B" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).B">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Time series break</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Observations are characterised as such when different content exists or a different methodology has been applied to this observation as compared with the preceding one (the one given for the previous period).</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="D" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).D">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Definition differs</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Used to indicate slight deviations from the established methodology (footnote-type information); these divergences do not imply a break in time series.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="E" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).E">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Estimated value</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Observation obtained through an estimation methodology (e.g. to produce back-casts) or based on the use of a limited amount of data or ad hoc sampling and through additional calculations (e.g. to produce a value at an early stage of the production stage while not all data are available). It may also be used in case of experimental data (e.g. in the context of a pilot ahead of a full scale production process) or in case of data of (anticipated/assessed) low quality. If needed, additional (uncoded) information can be provided through (free text) "comments" at the observation level or at a higher level.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="F" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).F">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Forecast value</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Value deemed to assess the magnitude which a quantity will assume at some future point of time (as distinct from "estimated value" which attempts to assess the magnitude of an already existent quantity).</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="G" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).G">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Experimental value</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Data collected on the basis of definitions or (alternative) collection methods under development. Data not of guaranteed quality as normally expected from provider.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="I" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).I">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Imputed value (CCSA definition)</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Observation imputed by international organisations to replace or fill gaps in national data series, in line with the recommendations of the United Nations Committee for the Coordination of Statistical Activities (CCSA).</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="M" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).M">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Missing value</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Data can be missing due to various reasons: data do not exist, are insignificant, are not collected (because they are below a certain threshold or subject to a derogation clause), are unreliable, are not relevant for the period, or other reason not elsewhere specified.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="P" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).P">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Provisional value</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">An observation is characterised as "provisional" when the source agency \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd while it bases its calculations on its standard production methodology \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd considers that the data, almost certainly, are expected to be revised.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="S" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).S">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Strike and other special events</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Special circumstances (e.g. strike) affecting the observation or causing a missing value.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="L" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).L">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Missing value; data exist but were not collected</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Used, for example, when some data are not reported/disseminated because they are below a certain threshold.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="H" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).H">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Missing value; holiday or weekend</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Used in some daily data flows.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="Q" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).Q">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Missing value; suppressed</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Used, for example, when data are suppressed due to statistical confidentiality considerations.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="J" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).J">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Derogation</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Clause in an agreement (e.g. legal act, gentlemen's agreement) stating that some provisions in the agreement are not to be implemented by designated parties; these derogations may affect the observation or cause a missing value. In general, derogations are limited in time.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="N" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).N">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Not significant</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Used to indicate a value which is not a "real" zero (e.g. a result of 0.0004 rounded to zero).</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="U" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).U">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Low reliability</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">This indicates existing observations, but for which the user should also be aware of the low quality assigned.</com:Description>         </str:Code>         <str:Code id="V" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Code=SDMX:CL_OBS_STATUS(1.1).V">           <com:Name xml:lang="en">Unvalidated value</com:Name>           <com:Description xml:lang="en">Observation as received from the respondent without further evaluation of data quality.</com:Description>         </str:Code>       </str:Codelist>       <str:Codelist id="CL_TIME_FORMAT" urn="urn:sdmx:org.sdmx.infomodel.codelist.Codelist=SDMX:CL_TIME_FORMAT(1.0)" agencyID="SDMX" version="1.0" isFinal="true">         <com:Name xml:lang="en">Time Format</com:Name>         <com:Description xml:lang="en">This code list provides coded information (based on the ISO 8601 standard) indicating the type of time references used in the data. codes; general guidelines for the creation of SDMX code lists) can be found at this address: http://sdmx.org/?page_id=1513.</com:Description>         <str:Code id="203"
